<subSubSection id="2CEF6546650404772AD66DD4FD55DE0F" pageId="5" pageNumber="254" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="644A36CD650404772AD66DD4FD55DE0F" blockId="5.[151,1437,151,573]" pageId="5" pageNumber="254">
<emphasis id="5681EADF650404772AD66DD4FE50DDE2" bold="true" box="[199,502,438,465]" pageId="5" pageNumber="254">Distribution and Biology.</emphasis>
The species has been collected at two sites using pitfall traps and is ground living in woodland west of the Great Dividing Range in north-eastern 
<collectingRegion id="A631F82F6504047729956DB9FBF5DDC7" box="[900,1107,475,501]" country="Australia" name="New South Wales" pageId="5" pageNumber="254">New South Wales</collectingRegion>
(
<figureCitation id="FCCE2A48650404772E776DB9FB08DDC7" box="[1126,1198,475,501]" captionStart="FIGURES 2–9" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1915,1939]" captionTargetBox="[169,1433,181,1891]" captionTargetId="figure-20@4.[151,1435,181,1891]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 2–9. Barraina abeddar n. sp. Holotype (KS74248), (female; 2 dorsal, 3 ventral, 4 lateral, 5 anterior views); (epigyne; external, 6, dissected and cleared, 7 dorsal, 9 ventral views); 9 distribution map. Scale: 0.2mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6592709" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6592709/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="254">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
). Due to the limited distribution data, recommended IUCN Red List Category DD. Because of its limited known range it may be at risk through climate change or habitat loss or degradation.
</paragraph>
